```

Creating a record (via the admin for example) with an empty value for `slug` produces the error: "AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'strip'".
It's raised when `SlugField.clean()` is called, executing `value = self.to_python(value).strip()`.
Source code: https://github.com/django/django/blob/1.8.7/django/forms/fields.py#L1258

# Context

At the moment, there is no distinction between coercion and validation. However there's been some suggestion that this should change. In particular #335, and the proposition of chaining brought up questions about whether coercion was superfluous in that case. My impression is that separating coercion from validation would enable order agnostic validator chaining, while having only one coercion method.

# What if...

```python
class MyClass(HasTraits):

    name = Unicode()
    
    @validate("name")
    def _my_name_is(self, value):
        return value.replace("my name is: ", "")
    
    @validate("_my_name_is")
    def _capitalize(self, value):
        return value[0].upper() + value[1:]

mc = MyClass()
mc.name = "my name is: ryan"
print(mc.name)

>>> Ryan
```

I suggest this concept because I seems that the resistance to the idea of chained validation (irrespective of coercion vs validation) stems from the fact that there's no real way to intuitively enforce order to multiple validators right now. If it were, `TraitType.allows` from #335 would be much more tenable since chaining wouldn't be a feature which was exclusive to that method.

I have not implemented this concept yet, because I'd like to know whether it's reasonable first.

cc: @minrk @SylvainCorlay @burnpanck

